'''Nishan Matthew Velupillay''' ({{langx|ta|நிஷான் மேத்யூ வேலுப்பிள்ளை}}, {{IPA|ta|niːʃɑːn ʋeːlupːiɭɭai|pron}};<ref>https://www.instagram.com/reel/DPj8zmvCdIx/?igsh=MWJzMXdmZWZob2kwbA==</ref> born 7 May 2001) is an Australian professional [[association football|soccer]] player who plays as a [[Winger (association football)|winger]] for [[Melbourne Victory FC|Melbourne Victory]] and the [[Australia men's national soccer team|Australia national team]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.melbournevictory.com.au/player/nishan-velupillay|title=Nishan Velupillay|date=20 November 2019}}</ref>

== Early life ==
Velupillay's father, Sasinath Velupillay is Malaysian with [[Sri Lankan Tamil]] heritage, while his mother, Gillian Velupillay, is [[Anglo Indian]]. He grew up in Australia. <ref>{{cite web |last1=De Silva |first1=Chris |title=Nishan Velupillay, Socceroos' newest goalscoring sensation, has key role in representing South Asian community |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2025-05-16/football-socceroos-nishan-velupillay-feature-next-generation/105265160 |website=ABC News |date=15 May 2025 |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |access-date=26 May 2025}}</ref>

== Club career ==

=== Early career ===
Velupillay began his career in the youth academy at Glen Eira FC, FTS (football technique school).<ref>{{Cite news |date=2021-11-18 |title=23 under 23: The best young players to look out for this A-League Men's season |language=en-AU |work=ABC News |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2021-11-19/a-league-men-players-to-watch/100609542 |access-date=2022-06-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=2025-05-16 |title=Nishan Velupillay, Socceroos' newest goalscoring sensation, has key role in representing South Asian community |language=en-AU |work=ABC News |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2025-05-16/football-socceroos-nishan-velupillay-feature-next-generation/105265160|access-date=2025-05-22}}</ref>

=== Melbourne Victory ===
Velupillay signed his first professional contract with [[Melbourne Victory FC|Melbourne Victory]] in 2019. He made his professional debut for the club on 19 May 2021, coming on as a substitute in a 0–2 defeat against Sydney. On 11 December 2021, Velupillay scored his first professional goal, netting the winning goal in a 2–1 win over [[Adelaide United FC|Adelaide United]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Australia - N. Velupillay - Profile with news, career statistics and history - Soccerway |url=https://my.soccerway.com/players/nishan-velupillay/643671/ |access-date=2022-06-26 |website=my.soccerway.com}}</ref> In the [[2024 A-League Men finals series|2024 finals series]] Velupillay would score a late goal in the 88th minute in an elimination final against [[Melbourne City FC|Melbourne City]], to make the scores level and put the match into [[extra-time]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Pisani |first=Sacha |title=Melbourne Victory vs Melbourne City, A-League Men, 5th May 2024 |url=https://aleagues.com.au/match/a-league-men/melbourne-victory-vs-melbourne-city-05-05-2024/ |access-date=2025-06-03 |website=A-Leagues |language=en-AU}}</ref> In the [[2024–25 Melbourne Victory FC season|2024-25 season]] Velupillay would become the clubs top goal-scorer for Melbourne Victory in all competitions and equal top goal-scorer for the club in the regular season. Unfortunately Velupillay would miss out on playing in the [[2025 A-League Men Grand Final|2025 A-League Grand final]] against [[Melbourne City FC|Melbourne City]], due to an injury.<ref>{{Cite web |last=jamesdodd |date=2025-05-28 |title=Nishan Velupillay injury latest: Victory boss provides update ahead of Grand Final |url=https://aleagues.com.au/news/nishan-velupillay-injury-latest-news-melbourne-victory-mitch-langerak/ |access-date=2025-06-03 |website=A-Leagues |language=en-AU}}</ref>

==International career==
In October 2024, Velupillay was called up by [[Tony Popovic]] ahead of their [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification – AFC second round|2026 FIFA World Cup qualifying]] matches against [[China national football team|China]] and [[Japan national football team|Japan]]. On 10 October, in the match against China, he came off the bench in the 83rd minute to replace [[Mitch Duke|Mitchell Duke]] to mark off his international debut. 7 minutes later, he scored his first international goal to seal a 3–1 win.

Further goals from Velupillay for the [[Australia men's national soccer team|Socceroos]] came in the March qualifying window for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]]. He scored in both games that window, first against [[Indonesia national football team|Indonesia]] and then followed by China 5 days later, with this being the second time he had scored against the Chinese national team. These two goals were a part of a 6 game scoring streak for Velupillay for club and country.

